  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "Explain the CAP theorem in distributed systems. Why can you only have two of three?",
  "response_text": "The CAP theorem, proposed by Eric Brewer in 2000, is a fundamental concept in distributed systems. It states that it's impossible for a distributed database system to simultaneously provide all three of the following guarantees:\n\n1. **Consistency (C)**: All nodes see the same data at the same time.\n2. **Availability (A)**: Every request receives a response, without guarantee that it's the most recent version of the data.\n3. **Partition Tolerance (P)**: The system continues to function when network partitions occur.\n\nThe reason we can only have two of these guarantees is due to the nature of distributed systems. In such systems, nodes communicate with each other via a network, and network failures or partitions are common. To ensure consistency, a distributed system may need to wait for all nodes to agree on the state of the data, which can lead to delays or unavailability. On the other hand, to ensure availability, a system may return a response even if some nodes are unavailable, which can lead to inconsistencies. To maintain partition tolerance, a system may need to sacrifice consistency or availability, as it must continue to function even when network partitions occur.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 0 (This question does not require affective modeling)\nF (Flexibility): 10\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
